Reasoning: The claim states that UCB T cells reduce TCR diversity after transplantation. However, evidence from paper ID 27910499, titled "Quantitative assessment of T-cell repertoire recovery after hematopoietic stem cell transplantation," directly refutes this. Proposition 4 from this paper states, "After 6 months, cord blood-graft recipients approximated the TCR diversity of healthy individuals." The abstract of the same paper further clarifies that "cord blood-graft recipients approximated the TCR diversity of healthy individuals, whereas recipients of T cell-depleted peripheral-blood stem cell grafts had 28-fold and 14-fold lower CD4(+) and CD8(+) T cell diversities, respectively." This indicates that cord blood (UCB) grafts lead to a recovery of TCR diversity to healthy levels, rather than a reduction. In contrast, T cell-depleted peripheral-blood stem cell grafts were associated with reduced TCR diversity.
